1. How does Meta earn money from Llama 3?

Meta developed the Llama family of models.

You can download and use Llama 3 for free under Meta's license (subject to its terms).

So why would Meta spend billions of dollars training an AI model and then release it?

Main reason: Grow the AI ecosystem

Imagine Microsoft released Windows for free to developers.

More people would build software for Windows.

That makes Windows more valuable.

Meta uses a similar strategy.

Meta
    │
Creates Llama
    │
Millions of developers use it
    │
More AI applications
    │
More influence in AI
    │
Business opportunities

====


How Meta actually earns money
1. Advertising

This is still Meta's biggest business.

Facebook
Instagram
WhatsApp Business
Threads

Better AI improves:

Personalized feeds
Better recommendations
Better ads
AI assistants

Better AI → Better user experience → More engagement → More advertising revenue.

====

2. Enterprise partnerships

Large companies often pay for:

AI consulting
Infrastructure
Enterprise integrations
Support services

Even if the model itself is available, businesses often spend money on surrounding services.

====


3. Open-source strategy

If millions of developers build on Llama:

Universities teach it.
Startups adopt it.
Companies integrate it.

This increases Meta's influence and helps establish its technology as a standard.

====

2. How does Ollama earn money?

Ollama created software that runs AI models locally.

The desktop software is free.

Their business opportunities include:

Enterprise deployments
Commercial support
Managed services
Future paid offerings

Many companies follow a similar model: a free core product with paid business services.

====

Real-world Example

Imagine your AI Meeting Notes Summarizer becomes popular.

You might offer:

Free version
5 meeting summaries/day
Basic features
Paid version
Unlimited summaries
Team collaboration
PDF exports
Priority support
API access

Thousands use the free version.

Some businesses upgrade to the paid version.

This "freemium" model is common in software.

