Who pays for Llama?

For personal use:

✅ Usually free.

For companies:

They may pay cloud providers to host it.
They pay for GPUs and infrastructure.
They pay engineers to build and maintain AI systems.
They may purchase enterprise support from vendors.

Even if the model is free, running it at scale is not.

====

Why is OpenAI different?

OpenAI (ChatGPT) generally keeps its most advanced models as hosted services.

User
   │
ChatGPT
   │
OpenAI Servers
   │
Monthly subscription/API fees

OpenAI earns revenue from:

ChatGPT subscriptions
API usage
Enterprise plans

===

Why is Llama different?
User
   │
Download Llama
   │
Run on own computer
   │
No payment to Meta for the model itself

However, the user or organization still pays for:

Their own computer or servers
Electricity
GPUs (if needed)
Maintenance

====

Another Example: Android

Google releases Android as open source.

Phone manufacturers use it for free.

How does Google benefit?

More Android phones
More Google Search
More Google Play usage
More advertising revenue

Meta is using a similar ecosystem-building strategy with Llama.

===


Summary

| Company | Free Product                       | Main Revenue Sources                                           |
| ------- | ---------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------------- |
| Meta    | Llama models                       | Advertising, AI ecosystem growth, enterprise opportunities     |
| Ollama  | Local AI runtime                   | Enterprise services, commercial support, future paid offerings |
| OpenAI  | Limited free ChatGPT + paid models | ChatGPT subscriptions, API usage, enterprise services          |
| Google  | Android (open source)              | Search, ads, cloud services, app ecosystem                     |


====

In short
Llama 3 is free because Meta wants widespread adoption of its AI technology, while continuing to earn most of its revenue from advertising and related business opportunities.
Ollama is free because its core runtime encourages adoption, with opportunities to earn from enterprise-focused services and support rather than charging individual users 
for the software itself.

